name: aluminium collector foil production, for Li-ion battery | aluminium collector foil, for Li-ion battery | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/24698/documentation

The dataset represents the production of 1 kg aluminium foil to be used as current collector for the positive electrode (cathode) in Lithium-ion battery. Input materials for pre-treatment, infrastructure and waste are included. ;The dataset has been partly extrapolated from Notter et al. (2010). ;;Reference: Notter, D. A., Gauch, M., Widmer, R., Wager, P., Stamp, A., Zah, R., & Althaus, H. J. (2010). Contribution of Li-ion batteries to the environmental impact of electric vehicles.

The activity starts with aluminium alloy and chemicals entering the factory.

The activity ends with the production of aluminium current collector foil at the factory gate.
category: C:Manufacturing/27:Manufacture of electrical equipment/279:Manufacture of other electrical equipment/2790:Manufacture of other electrical equipment

processDocumentation.timeDescription: The time period is from 2010 (year of the publication) and 2020 (year of the dataset)
processDocumentation.geographyDescription: The specific geography of aluminium foil production is unknown. This dataset is assumed to be valid for global conditions.
processDocumentation.technologyDescription: This dataset includes the pre-treatment process of aluminium foil. The alkaline cleaning is performed by using sodium hydroxide (NaOH) in order to remove grains and impurities, and form a protection layer against corrosion.
processDocumentation.dataTreatmentDescription: Data on chemicals for the pretreatment of aluminium foil are based on Notter et al. (2010). See comment to exchanges.

exchanges.description:
Alkaline cleaning processes are based on sodium hydroxide (NaOH) solutions. Some oxide particles and intermetallics, which are insoluble in the alkaline solution, form a ‘smut layer’ which loosely attaches to the aluminium surfaces. As a result, alkaline cleaning must be followed by an acid de-smutting step. 

This is a calculated value, representing the amount of H2SO4 necessary to neutralize NaOH used for the pre-treatment of aluminium foil. Based on stoichiometric calculation, following the reaction  2NaOH + H2SO4 = Na2SO4 + H2O. Therefore 1 kg NaOH is neutralized with 0.62 kg H2SO4. NaOH = 39.99 g/mol; H2SO4 = 99.036 g/mol
